WEBVTT

00:08.100 --> 00:11.300
Well, I'll have to run this by
the station manager, of course,

00:11.600 --> 00:13.400
but barring
any unforeseen circumstances,

00:13.700 --> 00:16.700
I believe the internship will be yours.

00:17.000 --> 00:18.000
That would be wonderful.

00:18.200 --> 00:21.500
But just meeting the preeminent
radio psychologist of this era

00:21.700 --> 00:23.600
has been a most thrilling experience.

00:24.200 --> 00:25.800
Well...

00:26.100 --> 00:27.200
[FRASIER CHUCKLES]

00:27.500 --> 00:28.500
So, Roz, what do you think?

00:28.700 --> 00:31.800
I think he's a pretentious,
arrogant toady.

00:32.100 --> 00:33.500
I love him too. Ha, ha.

00:34.100 --> 00:35.300
Just think of it, Roz.

00:35.600 --> 00:39.700
A triple major at Harvard University.
Why, he even plays the samisen.

00:40.100 --> 00:42.200
Oh, come on, Roz, the samisen.

00:42.500 --> 00:44.400
It's a Japanese
guitar-like instrument

00:44.700 --> 00:47.800
whose strings are plucked
with a spatula. Hmm?

00:48.600 --> 00:52.100
I can hardly wait
for the intern talent show.

00:52.500 --> 00:56.800
Oh, I'm so excited, Roz. At last
I'll have a superior mind I can mould.

00:59.100 --> 01:00.800
Speaking of mould,
what is he doing here?

01:00.900 --> 01:02.200
Are you still tutoring him?

01:02.500 --> 01:03.800
Oh, God forbid. Kirby.

01:04.099 --> 01:05.800
- Hey, Dr. Crane.
- Hello. Ha, ha.

01:06.000 --> 01:08.700
- Hello, Roz.
- Hi, Kirby.

01:09.100 --> 01:11.400
What have you been doing
since I took you to my prom?

01:11.700 --> 01:14.000
Mostly showering.

01:15.500 --> 01:17.000
So, what brings you here,
Kirby, hmm?

01:17.300 --> 01:19.200
I heard your station's
looking for an intern.

01:19.900 --> 01:24.100
Radio station's looking for an intern,
you say? Uh...

01:24.500 --> 01:26.500
I was hoping you could hook me up.

01:26.800 --> 01:28.100
Just think, with me working here,

01:28.300 --> 01:31.800
we'll be together,
like, 24/7, five days a week.

01:33.900 --> 01:35.600
Okay.

01:38.300 --> 01:40.200
I was hoping
you could go over my résumé.

01:40.400 --> 01:42.700
Oh, well, uh, all right, Kirby.

01:43.000 --> 01:44.900
Uh, although I must tell you that

01:45.200 --> 01:48.700
the station manager
has final say in these matters.

01:49.200 --> 01:51.000
I fudged a little bit on my job history.

01:51.400 --> 01:54.300
So you never actually worked
at NASA.

01:55.500 --> 01:57.500
Or Burger King. Heh.

01:59.800 --> 02:01.800
Hey, doc. Oh, is this one
of the intern candidates?

02:02.100 --> 02:04.000
- Uh, well...
- Kenny Daly. I'm the station manager.

02:04.300 --> 02:06.800
Pleased to meet you.
I'm so stoked to get this job.

02:07.100 --> 02:09.500
Oh, I like that in a candidate, doc.
He looks hungry.

02:09.800 --> 02:13.900
That's amazing, dude,
because I am kind of hungry.

02:14.300 --> 02:16.400
KENNY: There's a vending machine
right out there.

02:16.700 --> 02:19.100
Hey, I love this guy.
He's a breath of fresh air.

02:19.400 --> 02:22.600
Not like all these lvy League snobs
you've been prancing around all day.

02:23.500 --> 02:25.600
You're not really thinking
of hiring Kirby, are you?

02:25.800 --> 02:27.900
Of course not, Roz.
I've got my heart set on Lucius.

02:28.100 --> 02:30.900
- Me too. He plays the samisen.
- Yes, all right.

02:33.300 --> 02:35.600
Uh, Kirby, uh...

02:35.900 --> 02:38.400
Listen, I'm terribly sorry
about what just happened, um...

02:38.700 --> 02:39.700
What?

02:39.800 --> 02:40.900
[FRASIER SIGHS]

02:41.100 --> 02:43.900
You see, whenever Kenny sends
someone out to the candy machine,

02:44.100 --> 02:50.200
it's a signal that that person
won't be around anymore.

02:51.900 --> 02:54.800
We call it the Hershey's kiss-off.

02:55.800 --> 02:57.300
Man.

02:57.600 --> 03:01.800
I really want to get this job so I can
move in with Squoojy and Fat Tyler.

03:02.100 --> 03:05.000
You know, live like an adult
for once in my life.

03:05.900 --> 03:08.300
Yes, well, I am terribly sorry.

03:08.600 --> 03:10.600
It's not your fault.
You did everything you could.

03:10.900 --> 03:12.300
Well...

03:12.500 --> 03:14.800
Yes, l...
You know, I tell you what.

03:15.100 --> 03:18.500
Um, I will keep my ears open
for any opportunities, all right?

03:18.800 --> 03:21.600
That would be great. Something in
law enforcement would be awesome.

03:22.000 --> 03:27.000
Yes, well, that shouldn't be too difficult
considering you were trained...

03:27.300 --> 03:29.600
...by the FBO.

03:36.100 --> 03:37.000
[VELCRO TEARING]

03:37.300 --> 03:39.900
- Leave it, old man.
- Oh.

03:40.200 --> 03:41.200
It's bugging me.

03:41.400 --> 03:44.700
I do not have high blood pressure,
and it looks ridiculous.

03:45.000 --> 03:46.500
I think it looks handsome.

03:46.700 --> 03:50.400
Like those armbands gladiators wore,
only inflatable.

03:52.500 --> 03:54.000
- Ah, Daphne, Dad.
MARTIN: Hey, Fras.

03:54.700 --> 03:56.900
- Say, how was the doctor's?
- It stunk.

03:57.200 --> 03:58.900
Mr. Crane's pressure
read a little high,

03:59.200 --> 04:02.200
so Dr. Stewart insisted
he wear this monitor for 48 hours.

04:02.600 --> 04:04.300
- My, that's troubling.
DAPHNE: Don't worry.

04:04.500 --> 04:07.400
It's just a precaution. It takes
his pressure at random intervals,

04:07.800 --> 04:10.200
and sends the information
to a computer in the doctor's office.

04:10.500 --> 04:11.600
FRASIER: Oh.
- Very clever.

04:11.700 --> 04:13.800
It's not clever.
It's an invasion of my privacy.

04:14.100 --> 04:16.800
Plus, they got me
on that damn Heart Smart diet.

04:17.100 --> 04:18.899
Two days of salt and fat gone.

04:19.100 --> 04:20.100
[SNAPS]

04:21.399 --> 04:23.500
You don't get that back.

04:25.300 --> 04:27.800
Well, stay calm
or you'll be on it forever.

04:28.000 --> 04:30.000
Well, how can I stay calm?

04:30.300 --> 04:32.700
Just sitting here expecting this thing
to go off any second.

04:32.900 --> 04:35.500
I'm afraid to move.
It's like I'm a prisoner.

04:35.800 --> 04:37.200
That's just like doctors, isn't it?

04:37.500 --> 04:39.900
They're always finding
some new way to torture you.

04:40.200 --> 04:41.900
Well, maybe I want
my blood pressure high.

04:42.200 --> 04:43.700
They ever think about that? I mean...

04:44.000 --> 04:45.900
[MONITOR BEEPS
THEN DRONING]

04:47.800 --> 04:49.600
There it goes.

04:50.500 --> 04:53.200
You sneaky bastard.

04:54.200 --> 04:58.000
Uh, Dad, you know,
here's a suggestion, if I may. Um...

04:58.300 --> 05:02.700
The next time you feel yourself
getting annoyed, take a deep breath,

05:03.000 --> 05:06.800
and then picture your anger
as a red balloon,

05:07.100 --> 05:12.900
drifting higher and higher
above the clouds till it disappears.

05:13.600 --> 05:15.600
And that'll get me back on nachos?

05:17.200 --> 05:19.400
- Well, I better get ready for work.
- Right.

05:19.700 --> 05:21.500
Did you get my shirt back
from the cleaners?

05:21.700 --> 05:23.300
It's in your room.
I laundered it myself.

05:23.600 --> 05:25.500
No sense paying
for dry-cleaning a work shirt.

05:25.800 --> 05:28.900
Well, yes, there is. I told you,
they make us buy them ourselves.

05:29.200 --> 05:31.200
And they cost a lot of money,
you know.

05:31.500 --> 05:34.000
Then I have to go all the way down
to the uniform supply house.

05:34.300 --> 05:36.500
You can't park there because
of the construction going...

05:36.700 --> 05:37.900
[MONITOR BEEPS
THEN DRONING]

05:38.100 --> 05:41.100
No, no, no! No, wait, wait, wait!

05:41.800 --> 05:43.300
Damn it all to hell!

05:44.500 --> 05:46.300
Oh, you have some messages,
Dr. Crane.

05:46.500 --> 05:48.300
A Kirby called at 4:00,

05:48.600 --> 05:51.100
then again at 4:20 and 4:45.

05:51.400 --> 05:53.500
It was upsetting your father.
I turned the ringer off.

05:53.800 --> 05:57.300
Oh, dear.
I promised him I'd help him find a job.

05:57.700 --> 06:00.000
There's so few
for which he's qualified.

06:00.300 --> 06:02.400
And with the proliferation
of self-serve gas stations,

06:02.600 --> 06:05.400
I'm afraid that narrows the field
even further.

06:07.100 --> 06:09.600
Why is it your responsibility
to help him?

06:09.900 --> 06:11.700
Well, truth is,
I really didn't do all I could

06:12.000 --> 06:14.300
to help him get a job
at the radio station.

06:14.500 --> 06:15.500
Poor Kirby.

06:15.700 --> 06:17.800
You know, maybe I should just
turn the ringer back on.

06:18.000 --> 06:19.700
[PHONE RINGS]

06:22.200 --> 06:23.600
Maybe after dinner.

06:25.700 --> 06:27.000
- Hello. Hey, Daphne.
- Oh, Niles.

06:27.200 --> 06:28.700
I'll get my things. Be just a minute.

06:28.900 --> 06:31.200
Oh, uh, care for a quick sherry
before you go?

06:31.500 --> 06:32.500
Well, thank you.

06:32.700 --> 06:35.600
So how was your weekend?

06:36.400 --> 06:38.600
- Fine, and yours?
- Good.

06:38.900 --> 06:42.100
You know,
something curious did happen though.

06:42.700 --> 06:47.400
I was in the cheese shop
and I ran into Reynolds.

06:49.700 --> 06:51.500
He told me
that he saw several bottles

06:51.800 --> 06:54.000
of Château Haut Brion '61
at your place.

06:54.300 --> 06:56.300
I wasn't aware that you had
the Brion '61.

06:56.600 --> 06:58.700
Really? Didn't I tell you?
I stumbled across a case.

06:58.900 --> 07:00.600
Really?
That's wonderful news, Niles.

07:00.800 --> 07:02.000
It's virtually unattainable.

07:02.200 --> 07:04.200
So how much do I owe you
for my half?

07:04.500 --> 07:07.900
Ha, ha. That's very funny.
Reynolds made that same joke.

07:08.300 --> 07:10.200
Niles, we had a deal.

07:10.400 --> 07:13.100
Whenever I've found a case
of rare wine, I've offered you half.

07:13.400 --> 07:18.600
I understood our deal only applied
to vintages post-1965.

07:19.100 --> 07:20.500
That wasn't part of the agreement.

07:20.700 --> 07:21.900
Well, I'll have to re-read it.

07:22.200 --> 07:23.300
It was oral.

07:23.500 --> 07:25.600
Oh, pity.

07:26.800 --> 07:29.700
This is outrageous. I can't believe
you're cutting me out like this.

07:30.000 --> 07:31.300
I'm sorry.

07:31.500 --> 07:33.600
I try to be an ethical person
but wine is my weakness,

07:33.900 --> 07:37.200
and this is really too good to share.

07:37.500 --> 07:39.000
I see.

07:39.200 --> 07:42.800
- I will find a way to make it up to you.
- Why don't you just sell me my half?

07:43.200 --> 07:45.400
I said, I'll find a way
to make it up to you.

07:46.700 --> 07:49.300
- No, you have my word.
- Really?

07:49.600 --> 07:53.100
Your oral agreements aren't worth
the air into which they are uttered.

07:54.400 --> 07:56.900
- Are we ready to go?
- Yeah.

07:57.200 --> 07:58.900
Look, Daphne, I was, uh...

07:59.200 --> 08:02.000
I was thinking rather than go
to another boring movie,

08:02.400 --> 08:06.100
why don't we go back to my place,
and kick off our shoes,

08:06.400 --> 08:09.200
and, uh, rearrange my library?

08:09.400 --> 08:11.900
Are you still doing that?
You said you'd be finished by now.

08:12.300 --> 08:14.600
Yes, he says a lot of things.

08:16.800 --> 08:18.600
It's a bigger project
than I'd anticipated.

08:18.800 --> 08:21.700
- Can't you hire someone to help you?
- Let someone else touch my books?

08:22.000 --> 08:24.800
Where will I find someone with
your unimpeachable fastidiousness?

08:25.100 --> 08:26.900
- Fastidious, you say?
NILES: Mm-hm.

08:27.200 --> 08:31.400
You know, Niles, I believe I know
just the lad that can help you.

08:31.800 --> 08:33.100
Kirby Gardner.

08:33.299 --> 08:34.700
Isn't he that boy who's been calling?

08:35.000 --> 08:37.799
Yes, yes, he's very persistent,
one of his many fine attributes.

08:38.000 --> 08:39.700
And, you know,
I wanted to hire him myself,

08:40.000 --> 08:42.100
but there was nothing available
for him at the station.

08:42.400 --> 08:46.400
I don't know. My books
are the one thing I'm fussy about.

08:49.500 --> 08:51.200
Oh, please, Niles.

08:51.500 --> 08:53.700
It would give us more time together.

08:54.000 --> 08:56.100
- Well, if you put it that way.
- Ha-ha-ha.

08:56.400 --> 08:57.600
Wait.

08:57.800 --> 09:02.400
If I hire this protégé of yours,
will that make us even on the wine?

09:03.900 --> 09:07.200
Niles, you are too crafty for me.

09:08.900 --> 09:12.400
All right, yes, very well.
That will make us even. Ha-ha-ha.

09:12.800 --> 09:14.400
- Have a good night, you two.
- Thank you.

09:14.500 --> 09:16.500
[FRASIER CHUCKLES]

09:22.400 --> 09:23.600
NILES:
How's it going, Kirby?

09:23.700 --> 09:27.000
Hope you're not getting lost
in the 17th...

09:30.000 --> 09:32.300
Oh, look.

09:32.600 --> 09:33.600
Kirby!

09:34.100 --> 09:35.200
Kirby!

09:35.400 --> 09:36.800
Hey, Dr. Crane.

09:37.100 --> 09:39.600
What are you doing?
You're eating in my library.

09:39.900 --> 09:42.300
You're ruining my books.

09:42.500 --> 09:44.700
Relax, bro. I'm wearing the gloves.

09:49.800 --> 09:52.900
Kirby! Come down here.

09:54.800 --> 09:56.200
No, no, bring your can.

10:00.500 --> 10:02.200
Sit down.

10:03.600 --> 10:04.700
Kirby,

10:04.900 --> 10:08.000
this is completely unacceptable.
L... I just cannot allow this.

10:08.400 --> 10:11.000
- Whoa. Are you gonna fire me?
- Wha...?

10:11.700 --> 10:15.700
I know that you have good intentions,
but I'm afraid...

10:16.100 --> 10:17.300
[PHONE RINGING]

10:17.500 --> 10:19.100
Excuse me.

10:20.800 --> 10:22.300
Hello.

10:24.200 --> 10:26.000
It's for you.

10:27.000 --> 10:28.700
Could you find out who it is?

10:30.500 --> 10:32.600
Who's calling, please?

10:34.300 --> 10:36.400
It's Kristi Mulvehill.

10:36.700 --> 10:39.100
Tell her I'll call her back.

10:40.300 --> 10:42.100
He'll call you back.

10:42.600 --> 10:46.400
Kirby, your friend Kristi,

10:46.700 --> 10:48.900
she's not related
to William Mulvehill?

10:49.200 --> 10:50.600
Yeah, that's her grandfather.

10:51.400 --> 10:54.600
It's so weird how all you old dudes
all know each other.

10:56.200 --> 10:58.100
Well, I don't actually know him.

10:58.300 --> 11:02.100
Just know of him,
and his wine collection.

11:02.500 --> 11:04.000
Wine collection.

11:04.200 --> 11:05.900
It's famous among the old dudes.

11:06.100 --> 11:10.600
Legendary, except he's so reclusive
no one gets to see it.

11:10.900 --> 11:12.300
Frasier and I have tried everything

11:12.600 --> 11:15.900
but sealing ourselves in casks
and rolling in.

11:17.200 --> 11:19.300
Really? I go there a lot.

11:19.500 --> 11:22.000
You've been
to the Mulvehill wine cellar?

11:22.300 --> 11:25.300
Have you seen the bottle
that was owned by Thomas Jefferson?

11:25.700 --> 11:27.300
Well, I'm usually with Kristi,

11:27.500 --> 11:30.500
so, uh, I'm looking at the jugs,
not the bottles,

11:30.800 --> 11:32.700
if you know what I mean.

11:33.000 --> 11:36.100
Oh, I do. Ha, ha.

11:37.400 --> 11:39.200
You know, ahem,

11:39.500 --> 11:41.200
it would be a thrill
for a connoisseur like me

11:41.500 --> 11:46.100
to meet William Mulvehill.
Do you think you could get me in?

11:46.500 --> 11:47.700
I bet Kristi could.

11:48.100 --> 11:51.000
Well, let's just get her on the phone
and ask her, shall we?

11:51.500 --> 11:54.200
Well, I would,

11:54.400 --> 11:57.800
but if I were unemployed,
I'd just be too depressed to talk to her.

11:58.200 --> 12:00.000
Oh, unemployed,
what are you talking about?

12:00.300 --> 12:03.100
That was just a few harsh words
spoken in a moment of haste.

12:03.400 --> 12:05.100
The library
isn't challenging enough for you.

12:05.400 --> 12:09.100
We'll find something more suited
to your particular talents.

12:09.400 --> 12:10.400
Here's the phone.

12:10.600 --> 12:11.600
[DOORBELL RINGS]

12:11.900 --> 12:12.800
Oh.

12:13.000 --> 12:14.800
That'll be Frasier. Um...

12:15.100 --> 12:17.300
Why don't you call from the kitchen?

12:18.600 --> 12:20.500
Whoa.

12:20.800 --> 12:23.600
- Do they all do that?
- No! No!

12:28.600 --> 12:31.300
FRASIER: Niles.
- I'll be right there.

12:31.600 --> 12:33.300
Are you ready to...?

12:34.200 --> 12:36.900
Oh, dear.

12:37.500 --> 12:40.100
- Is this Kirby's work?
- Mm-hm.

12:40.400 --> 12:43.700
- Niles, I owe you an apology.
- No, no. I understand.

12:44.100 --> 12:47.000
- I had it coming. We're even.
- Let me help you clean up.

12:47.200 --> 12:50.100
No, don't be silly. I will be through this
in a trice. Just you scoot.

12:50.500 --> 12:52.400
- Nonsense. Let me help.
- No. No, really, please.

12:52.500 --> 12:53.700
- Niles, let me do...
- No.

12:54.000 --> 12:55.300
- Please.
- Oh, hi.

12:55.600 --> 12:59.400
Grampy Mulvehill says only
one person can go into the wine cellar.

13:00.500 --> 13:02.400
Grampy Mulvehill?

13:02.700 --> 13:04.700
As in William Mulvehill?

13:05.000 --> 13:07.700
I told you.
Old dudes, they all know each other.

13:08.700 --> 13:11.300
FRASIER:
I knew something was up.

13:11.600 --> 13:14.400
You weren't going to tell me
about Mulvehill, were you?

13:14.800 --> 13:15.900
I'm sorry.

13:16.100 --> 13:20.400
- I have <i>le vin fou</i>.
- Don't hand me that!

13:20.800 --> 13:23.200
That is just a flimsy excuse
for your outrageous selfishness.

13:23.400 --> 13:26.100
And what's worse,
is you're actually using that boy.

13:26.400 --> 13:29.300
Oh. Well, you used him
to get back at me.

13:29.600 --> 13:31.400
Yes, well, as you said,
it made us even.

13:31.700 --> 13:33.100
I said that to get you out of here.

13:33.200 --> 13:34.800
Look at my library!
I hope you're happy!

13:35.100 --> 13:36.500
I didn't think it would be this bad.

13:36.800 --> 13:38.900
I thought the boy could at least
put a book on a shelf!

13:39.200 --> 13:41.400
I can hear you fighting about me
from down the hall.

13:41.700 --> 13:43.900
- You're right, I don't deserve a job.
- That's not true.

13:44.200 --> 13:45.300
It is. Forget it.

13:45.400 --> 13:48.900
I'm a hopeless screw-up
just like my priest said.

13:49.300 --> 13:52.500
Kirby! Wait!

13:52.900 --> 13:54.200
[DOOR CLOSES]

13:54.500 --> 13:55.900
What happened?
What have we done?

13:56.200 --> 13:57.800
Well...

13:58.000 --> 14:00.000
Isn't it obvious, Niles?

14:00.300 --> 14:02.400
You've hurt his feelings.

14:05.400 --> 14:09.400
You know, I have
a special relationship with Kirby.

14:09.700 --> 14:14.500
Maybe I'll just take him out to dinner,
smooth things over.

14:14.900 --> 14:17.200
Well, I'm perfectly capable
of making my own apologies.

14:17.500 --> 14:19.000
I'll take him out to dinner.

14:19.200 --> 14:20.500
Well, you know, on second thought,

14:20.800 --> 14:24.300
I actually did say
some rather hurtful things myself.

14:24.600 --> 14:28.700
I think it's incumbent upon both of us
to help repair

14:29.000 --> 14:32.100
his damaged self-esteem together.

14:32.500 --> 14:37.100
Very well. We'll be two trained
therapists working in tandem.

14:37.500 --> 14:40.700
Yes.
To repair the wounded innocent.

14:41.000 --> 14:42.800
Yes. Yes, that's very high-minded
of you, Niles.

14:43.100 --> 14:45.000
Yes. You too, Frasier.

14:45.200 --> 14:48.500
You know, this is an utterly
altruistic act, isn't it?

14:48.700 --> 14:50.300
Utterly as it gets.

14:50.600 --> 14:52.200
I think we're of the same mind.

14:52.500 --> 14:54.700
Oh, I think so too.

15:02.800 --> 15:04.400
[DOOR OPENS]

15:04.700 --> 15:06.700
Where have you been? I'm starving.

15:06.900 --> 15:09.800
Sorry, I was walking Eddie.
Haven't even been to the market yet.

15:10.000 --> 15:13.200
Oh, Daph, it's almost 6:00.
How many times do I have to...?

15:14.900 --> 15:17.000
Red balloon.

15:20.200 --> 15:21.800
It's all right.

15:22.100 --> 15:24.600
Well, good for you.
And I'll nip out to the market now.

15:24.900 --> 15:26.800
No, don't bother.
Let's just open a can of soup.

15:27.100 --> 15:28.100
FRASIER:
Well, I'm off.

15:28.400 --> 15:30.200
- Enjoy your dinner.
- Thank you.

15:30.500 --> 15:32.500
You took the batteries
out of my remote.

15:32.800 --> 15:36.900
Gosh, I'm sorry, Dad.
I needed them for my foot spa.

15:37.200 --> 15:39.200
And you had to take them
out of the one thing

15:39.400 --> 15:41.000
I need batteries for in this house?

15:41.200 --> 15:44.600
God forbid your royal feet
go without eucalyptus...

15:45.000 --> 15:46.500
Dad.

15:52.000 --> 15:53.300
That's all right.

15:53.500 --> 15:55.600
There's gotta be some other way
to switch the channels.

15:55.900 --> 15:57.300
DAPHNE:
Bye.

15:57.600 --> 15:59.200
Well, I'll go and open
that can of soup.

15:59.500 --> 16:01.200
Oh, would you turn the game on?

16:01.300 --> 16:02.300
Sports?

16:02.600 --> 16:04.500
Hmm, might be a bit too exciting.

16:04.800 --> 16:07.200
Why don't we just watch
a nice, soothing movie?

16:07.600 --> 16:09.500
- Like what?
- How about <i>Message in a Bottle?</i>

16:09.800 --> 16:12.700
Is that one of those movies that takes
45 minutes for anything to happen,

16:13.000 --> 16:15.400
and then you're sorry it did?

16:16.400 --> 16:20.200
If you don't like that, we could watch
<i>To Gillian on Her 37th Birthday</i>.

16:28.300 --> 16:30.700
- You pick.
- Yes.

16:33.500 --> 16:36.000
- Niles.
- Well, imagine my surprise

16:36.200 --> 16:38.800
seeing the two of you here,
when the three of us have reservations

16:39.100 --> 16:41.300
for dinner at Le Cigare Volant
in half an hour.

16:41.600 --> 16:45.900
Hi, Dr. Crane. Dr. Crane invited me
here for a before-dinner cocoa.

16:46.400 --> 16:49.300
Isn't that nice?
Frasier, may I have a word?

16:49.600 --> 16:52.600
Yes, of course, Niles.
Kirby, we'll be right back.

16:54.400 --> 16:56.400
All right.
Now, before you get started,

16:56.700 --> 16:58.800
I brought the boy here in order
to ease him into this.

16:59.100 --> 17:02.100
I was afraid that the sight of us might
bring up some unpleasant memories.

17:02.500 --> 17:04.000
I see.
So this has nothing to do with you

17:04.200 --> 17:07.300
trying to get into Grampy Mulvehill's
wine cellar instead of me?

17:07.700 --> 17:11.700
The fact that you even said that
speaks volumes about you.

17:12.099 --> 17:14.800
Let's get back before the boy
starts to think we're talking about him.

17:15.599 --> 17:17.300
We're back now.

17:18.300 --> 17:21.400
Kirby, I just want to tell you
how sorry I am

17:21.800 --> 17:24.500
for both Frasier
and my behaviour earlier.

17:24.800 --> 17:26.000
It's no problem. I forgave you

17:26.300 --> 17:29.400
as soon as I got that DVD player
you sent me.

17:32.100 --> 17:33.900
Niles, may I see you for a moment?

17:37.900 --> 17:39.200
- DVD player?
- Okay.

17:39.500 --> 17:42.100
You caught me in a selfish moment.
I was trying to assuage my guilt

17:42.400 --> 17:43.500
for the way I treated him.

17:43.800 --> 17:46.800
You weren't trying to buy loyalty so you
could benefit from your connection,

17:47.100 --> 17:51.100
reviving your woefully flagging
reputation in the wine community?

17:52.000 --> 17:54.200
I categorically deny that.

17:54.500 --> 17:55.800
So you did it just to burn me?

17:56.000 --> 17:58.100
- I deny that.
- But not categorically.

17:58.400 --> 18:00.600
Frasier, do I have to remind you

18:00.900 --> 18:02.600
that this is not about us,
it's about Kirby,

18:02.900 --> 18:05.200
whom we've abandoned
in order to have this petty spat.

18:07.500 --> 18:09.600
FRASIER:
We're back again.

18:09.900 --> 18:12.700
So, Kirby, where were we?

18:13.000 --> 18:15.600
You were asking me
about Grampy's wine cellar.

18:15.800 --> 18:17.900
- Frasier?
- Not now, Niles.

18:18.100 --> 18:20.100
Fine. I was going to leave this
till later, but...

18:20.400 --> 18:24.200
Kirby, I saw these,
and I thought of you.

18:24.600 --> 18:26.200
No way!

18:26.300 --> 18:28.200
Thirteens. How'd you know my size?

18:28.600 --> 18:30.000
Oh, I measured the footprint you left

18:30.300 --> 18:33.400
in doughnut powder on my floor,
you rascal.

18:34.400 --> 18:36.000
These are awesome.
Aren't they, Dr. Crane?

18:36.100 --> 18:38.200
Oh, yes, indeed they are, Kirby.

18:38.500 --> 18:42.100
You know, you're going to need
some togs to go with them.

18:42.500 --> 18:43.700
I have an account at Bidwells.

18:43.900 --> 18:45.700
What do you say I call them
and set you up?

18:45.900 --> 18:49.300
Wow, thanks.
I never had togs before.

18:49.700 --> 18:50.700
You guys are so great,

18:51.000 --> 18:53.600
the way you keep trying to build up
my self-esteem and all.

18:53.800 --> 18:56.600
I wish there was some way
I could take you both to the wine cellar.

18:56.900 --> 18:58.900
But I can't.

19:01.300 --> 19:03.000
- Niles.
- Frasier.

19:06.000 --> 19:09.400
Do you believe the nerve of this boy,
pitting us against each other?

19:09.700 --> 19:11.200
We're not going to be manipulated.

19:11.400 --> 19:14.100
We certainly aren't.
All right, let's put a stop to it right now.

19:14.300 --> 19:16.200
All right,
I'm afraid your little game is up.

19:16.400 --> 19:18.900
- And I wanna tell you something else...
- A hundred dollars.

19:19.100 --> 19:21.400
- Two hundred dollars.
- Three hundred dollars.

19:21.600 --> 19:22.900
Five hundred dollars!

19:23.200 --> 19:25.900
- Kirby, have you ever been to Vegas?
FRASIER: He can't go to Vegas.

19:26.200 --> 19:29.000
He'll be too busy
interning at the radio station.

19:29.300 --> 19:31.100
No way.

19:31.400 --> 19:32.600
I got the job?

19:32.900 --> 19:35.900
Thank you, Dr. Crane.
You just got yourself a wine tour.

19:36.200 --> 19:39.800
Well, and thank you, Kirby.
Ha, ha!

19:40.200 --> 19:42.500
This is so awesome.
And I promise I will not let you down.

19:42.800 --> 19:45.100
I'm gonna soak up as much
as I can from you.

19:45.300 --> 19:47.400
I'm gonna be like your shadow.

19:47.700 --> 19:51.900
You and me, Dr. Crane.
From now on.

19:52.300 --> 19:55.200
You know,
we should probably car pool to work.

19:57.000 --> 19:59.700
- Niles, could I see you for a moment?
- No.

20:03.900 --> 20:06.700
Isn't this the most romantic thing
you've ever seen?

20:07.000 --> 20:08.900
If you say so.

20:10.000 --> 20:13.300
There's no greater passion than that
between a woman and a ghost.

20:13.600 --> 20:14.900
[SNIFFS]

20:16.000 --> 20:17.100
[PHONE RINGING]

20:17.300 --> 20:19.100
I'll get it.

20:24.600 --> 20:26.200
Hello?

20:26.900 --> 20:28.700
Oh, uh, yeah?

20:29.000 --> 20:30.500
Really?

20:30.700 --> 20:32.500
I don't have to wear it anymore?

20:32.800 --> 20:33.900
That's great.

20:34.000 --> 20:36.300
Yeah, thanks, Dr. Stewart.

20:37.900 --> 20:40.400
- Who was that?
- Dr. Stewart.

20:40.600 --> 20:43.000
- Are you all right?
- I'm fine.

20:43.200 --> 20:46.400
Hmm, I suppose you'll want me
to put the game on then.

20:47.300 --> 20:51.500
Well, uh, actually, he said there was
a bit of a foul-up with the computer,

20:51.800 --> 20:55.700
and, uh, maybe I should wear it
for a couple more hours.

20:57.800 --> 20:59.900
Well, that's too bad.

21:00.200 --> 21:01.300
Do you want me to rewind?

21:01.600 --> 21:03.800
If you're gonna keep talking!

21:16.600 --> 21:19.600
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]
